Here's the complete migration with key pitfalls explained:

## Migrated ASP.NET Core (.NET 8) Code

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // ASP.NET Core uses action methods returning IActionResult, not event handlers.
    // No postback model exists — use routes instead.

    [HttpPost("report/export")]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // FileContentResult replaces the entire Response.Clear/Write/End pattern.
        // No ThreadAbortException — the framework handles response completion.
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv"
        );
    }

    [HttpPost("report/redirect")]
    public IActionResult RedirectAfterProcess()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // RedirectResult issues a 302 — no thread abort, no boolean flag.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // No ThreadAbortException catch needed — Redirect() just returns
        // an IActionResult, it doesn't terminate the thread.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

### 1. `Response.End()` / `Response.Redirect(_, true)` → gone entirely
These called `Thread.Abort()` internally in Framework. ASP.NET Core has **no equivalent** — `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8. Return `IActionResult` instead of imperatively writing to the response.

### 2. Swallowing `ThreadAbortException` → dead code
```csharp
// FRAMEWORK — common pattern:
catch (ThreadAbortException) { } // "expected"

// .NET 8 — ThreadAbortException no longer exists as a runtime concept.
// Remove these catch blocks entirely. If left in, they compile but
// never execute (misleading).
```

### 3. `Response.Write()` + `Response.Clear()` → return `File()` / `Content()`
Imperatively writing to `HttpResponse` still *works* in Core (`Response.Body.WriteAsync`), but it **bypasses** MVC's result pipeline (filters, content negotiation). Use `IActionResult` returns.

### 4. WebForms event model → MVC routing
`btnExport_Click` postback handlers don't exist. Map them to `[HttpPost]` action methods with explicit routes. Update your forms:
```html
<!-- Old WebForms -->
<asp:Button ID="btnExport" runat="server" OnClick="btnExport_Click" />

<!-- ASP.NET Core -->
<form asp-action="Export" asp-controller="Report" method="post">
    <button type="submit">Export</button>
</form>
```

### 5. `User.Identity.IsAuthenticated` — null-safety
In Framework, `User.Identity` was never null. In Core it **can be null** if no auth middleware is configured. Always use `User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? false`.

### 6. Prefer `[Authorize]` over manual checks
```csharp
[Authorize]
[HttpPost("report/redirect")]
public IActionResult RedirectAfterProcess()
{
    // No manual IsAuthenticated check needed.
    // Unauthenticated users get 401 → redirected by auth middleware.
    ProcessRequest();
    return Redirect("/success");
}
```

Configure in `Program.cs`:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddAuthentication(/* ... */);
builder.Services.AddAuthorization();
// ...
app.UseAuthentication();
app.UseAuthorization();
```

### Quick Reference

| Framework Pattern | Core Equivalent |
|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | Return `IActionResult` |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `return Redirect(url)` |
| `Response.Write(data)` | `return Content(data)` |
| `Response.Clear()` + headers | `return File(bytes, mime, name)` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | **Delete it** |
| `Controller` (System.Web.Mvc) | `Controller` (Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc) |
